4\. AL Coding Standards

TES Prefix

**The default prefix that should be used in all scenarios is:**

&nbsp;

**TES**

Further detail will be provided below on in which scenario's not to use this prefix, e.g., the 'name' property of a customer-specific extension.

Folder Structure Conventions

There should be two folders per extension, one called 'App' which will include all files related to the extension and another one called 'Test' which will include all files related to the extensions testing extension.

Both two folders will include the following:

- app.json
- AL object files
- Images
- Any metadata / user specific files i.e.
  - .vscode\\launch.json
  - .alpackages\\dependencies

Within both folders, a subfolder should be created called 'src' and in this folder subfolders should be created for each type of object where the AL object files (.al) are stored.

There are two suitable structures for folders within the 'src' folder.

**Example 1: Objects by Object Type**

&nbsp;

- Pages
- Codeunits
- Reports
- Report Extensions
- Tables
- Table Extension
- Page Extension
- Profiles
- Enums
- Queries
- XMLPorts
- Request Page
- Enum Extension
- Control Add-Ins
- Dot Net
- Interfaces
- Permission Sets

File / Object Naming Conventions

The object name should be in this format:

\[ObjectName\].\[ObjectTypeName\].al

Note: In the table below for Object Name, TES is the Prefix used by Total Enterprise Solutions Ltd.

&nbsp;

| Object Type | Object Name | File Name |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Table | TES NFP Setup | NFPSetup.Table.al |
| Table Extension | TES Purchase Header | PurchaseHeader.TableExt.al |
| Page | TES NFP Setup | NFPSetup.Page.al |
| Page Extension | TES Purchase Order | PurchaseOrder.PageExt.al |
| Profiles | TES User | User.Profile.al |
| Codeunits | TES Create Data | CreateData.Codeunit.al |
| Queries | TES Query | Query.Query.al |
| XMLPorts | TES XMLPort | XMLport.XMLPort.al |
| Enumerations | TES Comm Event Type | CommEventType.Enum.al |
| Enum Extension | TES VAT Clause Document Type | VATClauseDocumentType.EnumExt.al |
| Report | TES Approval Instant | ApprovalInstant.Report.al |
| Report Extensions | TES Purchase Order - GB | PurchaseOrderGB.ReportExt.al |
| Permission Sets | TES General Modifications | GeneralModifications.PermissionSet.al |
| Interfaces | TES ICalculateAmount | ICalculateAmount.Interface.al |

&nbsp;

PTE extensions, which are customer-specific, do not require customer initials such as "TES CZ Purch. Events" within object names. TES IP apps will instead prefix with a module identifier to prevent conflicts, such as "TES DA".

CodeCop warning AA0215 can be used to suppress warnings for file naming conventions.

Field Naming Convention

New Field Names within table extensions must always start with the prefix **TES**

For example; if the Field "Job No." is added to an extended table, the field name must be:

TES Job No.

Formatting within AL Code

TES follow the following Microsoft guidelines:

- Use Pascal Case (this means every word starts with a capital letter)

e.g., OpenSalesQuote

&nbsp;

Note: Use lowercase letters for reserved language keywords.

&nbsp;

- Use four spaces for indentation  
- Curly brackets should be placed on a new line  
- If there is one property, this should be placed on a single line.

&nbsp;

Note:

The AL Formatter offers users the option to automatically format source code. As shown in the screenshot below you can use AL Format by using the keys Shift+Alt+F.

For more information on invoking AL Formatter, see [AL Formatter](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dynamics365/business-central/dev-itpro/developer/devenv-al-formatter).

File Structure

For all extensions, the file structure should be as follows:

- Properties  
- Object-specific constructs such as:

- Table fields  
- Page layout  
- Actions
- Triggers  

- Global variables

- Labels (old Text Constants)  
- Global variables  

- Methods  

Developers can use the AZ AL Dev Tools extension within Visual Studio Code to organize objects as described above.

&nbsp;

Referencing

In AL, objects are referenced by their object name, not by their ID.  

Example:

&nbsp;

Page.RunModal(Page::"Customer Card", ...)

&nbsp;

var

&nbsp;   Customer: Record Customer;

&nbsp;

Variable naming

Variables should be named in the following way:

- PascalCase
- Use the Temp Prefix if they are temporary variables.
- Include the object name in the name (for objects).

Furthermore:

- Field and variable names should not include wildcard symbols, such as % and &. This might break features such as export using Excel or Rapid Start.
- Name fields using aA-zZ and 0-9 and use Caption and xliff files to display the field appropriately.
- Using English as the language for naming improves the ability to troubleshoot issues that may arise.

Example

TempCustomer: Record Customer temporary;

Vendor: Record Vendor;

To assist in variable naming, it is suggested to add the following settings to your settings.json.

"alOutline.completionProviders": \[

"VariableNamesWithType",

"VariableDataTypes"

\]

This will prompt Intellisense to complete the Variable Name, Data Type and Object Name complying with the advised guidelines.

![A screenshot of a computer program

Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

Method Declaration

To declare a method, follow these guidelines:

- Include one space after a semicolon when declaring multiple arguments.
- Semicolons can be used at the end of the signature / method header. If you use a snipped, the semicolons are not automatically added.
- Methods are named as variables using Pascal Case.
- There must be a blank line between method declarations. If you format your code using the AL Formatter tool, the auto-formatter sets the blank line between procedures.

&nbsp;

Example

local procedure MyProcedure(Customer: Record Customer; Int: Integer)

begin

end;

&nbsp;

// space local procedure MyProcedure2(Customer: Record Customer; Int: Integer)

begin

end;

Calling Methods

When calling a method, include one space after each command if you are passing multiple parameters.

Parentheses must be specified when you are making a method call or system call such as: Init(), Modify(), Insert() etc.  

e.g:

OpenCustomer('C0001');

OpenCustomer('C0001', Customer);

&nbsp;

Type definition (colon)

When declaring a variable or a parameter, the name of that variable or parameter must be immediately followed by a colon, then a single space, and then the type of the variable/parameter as illustrated in the example below.

Example

var

Number: Integer;

local procedure MyProcedure(a: Integer; b: Integer): Integer

Line length  

In general, there is no restriction concerning line length, but lengthy lines can make the code unreadable. We recommend that you keep your code easily scannable and readable.  

Global and Local Variables & Procedures

It is best practice to keep variables and procedures local unless they have a direct intention of being used from external objects or apps.

Key Naming

When creating keys within AL table extensions add the extension prefix:

Example

Keys

{

key(TESKey1; "Posting Date")

}

- You can use the same key name in the table extension unless the key contains fields from the base table object.
- In Business Central 2021 release wave 1 and later, keys in table extension objects can include fields from the base table object and table extension object. However, a single key cannot include fields from both the base table object and table extension object. In other words, each key must contain fields from either the base table object or the table extension object.

App Configuration

For all extensions produced by TES the app json file should contain the following properties:

- "name": \[prefix\]\[name\]
  - \[prefix\] is either TES for TES IP, or an acronym of the customer's name if customer specific.
  - \[name\] is the name of the extension i.e., Document Approvals or General Enhancements.
- "publisher": "Total Enterprise Solutions",
- "logo": "./logo/Icon.png",

Commits

Any COMMIT; call should include a comment to justify its existence. This should be either a trailing or leading comment.

**Example**

// Required to call RUNMODAL Page in the following procedure

Commit;

Versioning

For all extensions produced by TES the app.json file should contain the version of the app based on the following:

An always increasing set of four integers, separated by a dot, i.e., X.X.X.X. Upon increasing one of the integers, each integer to its right can be reset to zero.

The format of each integer in the version must be as follows:

**Non-IP Extensions**

| X   | X   | X   | X   |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| BC Major Release<br><br>e.g., 23 | TES (Publisher) Release - starting at 0 | Patch Version - starting at 0 | Release date in yyyyMMdd<br><br>i.e., 20210329 for 29<sup>th</sup> March 2021 |

e.g 23.0.12345.0

**IP Extensions**

| X   | X   | X   | X   |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| BC Major Release<br><br>e.g., 23 | TES (Publisher) Release - starting at 0 | Build version of Azure Pipeline | Always 0 |

e.g 23.0.0.20240126

**Non-IP Extensions**

Each release to a production environment no matter how small the change must increase at least the Patch Version and update the Release Date to today's date. (Change Requests changing existing features (if the change to the existing feature is extensive enough this may be considered a new feature and require the TES Release updating as below)).

For changes such as the release of a new feature(s) the TES Release must be increased, the Patch Version reset to 0 and the Release Date set to today's date. (Project & Change Request new features).

Finally for a new release of BC e.g., 18, the BC Major Release must be increased according to the number of the BC major release, TES Release reset to 1, Patch version reset to 0 and the Release Date set to today's date.

e.g.

- 17.1.0.20210329 - for initial release on 29/03/2021
- 17.1.1.20210401 - patch released on 01/04/2021
- 17.1.2.20210416 - patch released on 16/04/2021
- 17.2.0.20210503 - major TES release for this version of BC on 03/05/2021
- 18.1.0.20210401 - Microsoft major BC release of version 18 on 01/04/2021

5\. Source Control

Projects

- TES IP

A TES IP project exists in the 'TES365' Organisation of the Azure DevOps site. There is a repository for each TES IP Product.

- Customer Specific Extensions

A project will exist per customer in the 'TES365' organisation within the TES Azure DevOps platform. Each of these projects will contain a repository for each customer specific extension, i.e., there is a 'Total Enterprise Solutions' project containing extensions for our internal Business Central system.

- Repositories

A repository will exist per extension, whether that be a module of NFP or a customer specific extension. The repository name should specify the system and extension name, such as 'BC - DocumentApprovals' or 'BC- GeneralModifications'.

- Branches
- main

All repositories have one main branch, it will contain the latest signed-off version of the extension that can be deployed to a Production environment. No other branches should be used when deploying to a production environment, except in the case of a new release or hotfix. Once a release or hotfix branch has been deployed, this must be pulled into the main branch.

Commits may only be pulled into the main branch via a pull request from either the release or hotfix branches, where unit, functional and automated testing, alongside any test scripts are required to have been completed with 100% success.

**Naming Convention**: master or main

- Release

All repositories will have a release branch created based on the master branch, which will then run continuously alongside the master/main branch. The release branch will contain all development that will be a part of this release once that development is ready to be tested and then signed off for release to a production environment.

Commits may only be pulled into the release branch via a pull request from either the development or hotfix branches, where unit and automated testing alongside any test scripts are required to have been completed with 100% success.

**Naming Convention**: release/CHG000000 / release/v23.0.1.0

Feature / Project / Change Request/ Bugs

A branch must be created for each new feature, project or change request to an extension.

Commits may be pushed into a feature branch and no testing needs to be completed.

**Naming Convention**: users/john-doe/CHG00300 **or** users/john-doe/#15533_AppDimSelection

Forks

Currently forks are not to be used as part of the development process.

Pull Requests

When moving code from one branch to another, a pull request must be used. As a part of completing a pull request (when you press "Complete"), you will be asked to select a "Merge Type," currently you should select "Squash commit."

Commits

Commits MUST end with the work item ID you are working on, in the format:

# {work-item-id}, e.g., #420

Following the above ID must be a more detailed explanatory text. Explain the problem that this commit is solving. Focus on why you are making this change as opposed to how (the code explains that). Are there side effects or other unintuitive consequences of this change? Here is the place to explain them.

Further paragraphs come after blank lines.

\- Bullet points are okay, too

\- Typically, a hyphen is used for the bullet, preceded

by a single space, with blank lines in between.

Code Reviews

Code reviews are an essential part of TES Quality Assurance. Software code reviews for Microsoft Dynamics 365 Business Central and Dynamics 365 are a crucial element of ensuring quality, security and maintainability of all Software developed by TES for its Customers.  

The key objectives of the TES Code Review process are:

- Ensure adherence to TES Development Guidelines and Coding Standards and thus ensuring delivery of a

quality solution to the customer.

- Enhancing team collaboration
- Promoting knowledge sharing among team members
- Identify bugs at an early stage.

### Roles and Responsibilities

TES Code Reviews can be conducted by one of several technical resources employed by Total Enterprise Solutions.  

Conducting a code review assumes significant responsibility and for this reason, colleagues authorised to conduct code reviews are recorded within the TES System and Roles Matrix.  

Conducting a code review requires a systematic and thorough approach to ensure code quality, maintainability, and adherence to TES Development and Coding Standards.  

### Scope of when Code Reviews are required

All pull requests for Release and Main / Default branches must go through the Code Review process that is described in the official Code Review Procedure. This procedure can be located via the official TES Master Documentation spreadsheet in the Development team on Microsoft teams.
